16:19.436 --> 16:21.146
<i>you know, people who said,</i>
<i>"But wait a minute,</i>

16:21.271 --> 16:25.567
you can't put money into this
and take it away from other things."

16:25.734 --> 16:27.194
And he said, "But we have to,

16:27.277 --> 16:29.196
because we have to learn
about this disease."

16:29.989 --> 16:32.574
DR. FAUCI: <i>I recruited young people</i>
<i>to work with me.</i>

16:32.908 --> 16:36.829
<i>Henry Masur, who was</i>
<i>on the junior faculty at Cornell,</i>

16:37.162 --> 16:39.707
<i>Cliff Lane had just finished</i>
<i>his fellowship</i>

16:40.249 --> 16:45.337
<i>and the three of us</i>
<i>became the Three Musketeers of HIV</i>

16:45.421 --> 16:46.588
<i>here at NIH.</i>

16:47.840 --> 16:52.011
Our focus at the time was
the adult human immune system.

16:52.094 --> 16:54.763
There weren't a lot of groups
that had that as a focus.

16:54.972 --> 16:57.057
You just knew you had to do something.

16:57.224 --> 16:58.892
Because you thought
you could do something.

16:59.018 --> 17:03.897
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

17:04.023 --> 17:06.692
TOM BROKAW: <i>Scientists</i>
<i>at the National Center For Disease Control</i>

17:06.817 --> 17:09.445
<i>in Atlanta today released the results</i>
<i>of a study</i>

17:09.570 --> 17:13.240
which shows that the lifestyle
of some male homosexuals

17:13.449 --> 17:16.493
has triggered an epidemic
of a rare form of cancer.

17:16.618 --> 17:19.246
ROBERT BAZELL:
<i>Researchers know of 413 people</i>

17:19.371 --> 17:21.790
<i>who have contracted the condition</i>
<i>in the past year.</i>

17:22.082 --> 17:24.710
<i>One third have died</i>
<i>and none have been cured.</i>

17:24.918 --> 17:26.837
How many friends have you lost
to this disease?

17:26.962 --> 17:28.005
Twenty.

17:28.088 --> 17:29.173
-JANE PAULEY: Twenty?
-Yes.

17:29.256 --> 17:31.383
JANE: And you have
still more friends who are sick?

17:31.467 --> 17:32.509
Very ill.

17:32.760 --> 17:36.180
Jane, can you imagine what it must be like
if you had lost 20 of your friends

17:36.263 --> 17:38.307
-in the last 18 months?
-JANE: No.

17:38.432 --> 17:42.061
-And you don't know why?
-No cause, no cure.

17:42.269 --> 17:44.063
BAZELL:<i> Investigators</i>
<i>have examined the habits</i>

17:44.188 --> 17:45.731
<i>of homosexuals for clues.</i>

17:45.856 --> 17:49.526
That I was in the fast lane at one time
in terms of the way that I lived my life

17:49.651 --> 17:50.778
and now I'm not.

17:50.861 --> 17:53.197
A-I-D-S. AIDS.

17:53.280 --> 17:55.532
The most frightening initials
in America today.

17:55.783 --> 17:58.577
<i>A medical mystery that destroys</i>
<i>the immune system</i>

17:58.911 --> 18:03.123
<i>and leaves our bodies defenseless</i>
<i>against unusual and deadly infections.</i>

18:04.708 --> 18:06.794
MALE VOICE 1:<i> I was going out</i>
<i>and meeting people,</i>

18:06.919 --> 18:07.961
<i>trying to find a lover.</i>

18:08.087 --> 18:10.798
I didn't know that, you know,
that there were things out there

18:10.881 --> 18:14.551
so secretly hidden
that it was gonna destroy my life.

18:20.099 --> 18:23.769
DR. FAUCI: <i>I had been trained</i>
<i>as an infectious disease doc...</i>

18:24.353 --> 18:25.771
<i>and as an immunologist.</i>

18:26.063 --> 18:29.983
If ever there was a disease
that I was made for...

18:30.859 --> 18:32.194
it's this disease.

18:34.321 --> 18:36.990
DAVID HARTMAN:<i> Dr. Fauci, can you tell us</i>
<i>what do we know?</i>

18:37.074 --> 18:38.367
<i>What are the best clues you've got?</i>

18:38.492 --> 18:40.911
DR. FAUCI:<i> We do have some clues</i>
<i>that it may be a viral agent</i>

18:41.036 --> 18:44.915
that is likely infecting immune cells
that are necessary to fight

18:45.082 --> 18:46.291
certain types of infections...

18:46.375 --> 18:52.256
We didn't know what it was.
We strongly suspected it was a virus.

18:52.506 --> 18:57.678
There is, right now at the present time,
no known cure for AIDS.

18:57.761 --> 19:01.390
We don't even know what the agent is,
much less how to cure it.

19:01.765 --> 19:03.725
GERALDO RIVERA:
<i>Like ink spreading on a blotter,</i>

19:03.809 --> 19:07.146
<i>AIDS has now been identified</i>
<i>in over 35 states</i>

19:07.271 --> 19:09.064
<i>and 16 foreign countries.</i>

19:09.398 --> 19:12.442
DR. FAUCI: <i>It was an evolving picture...</i>

19:13.318 --> 19:15.154
rapidly and frighteningly.

19:16.113 --> 19:18.073
MALE REPORTER:
<i>For the first time North America,</i>

19:18.407 --> 19:21.493
<i>the world's leading experts</i>
<i>on sexually transmitted diseases</i>

19:21.577 --> 19:23.996
<i>meet to share the latest research data.</i>

19:24.329 --> 19:28.167
<i>From the National Institutes of Health,</i>
<i>Dr. Anthony Fauci,</i>

19:28.417 --> 19:32.129
<i>who directs the research on how AIDS</i>
<i>affects the body's immune system.</i>

19:32.880 --> 19:36.800
From what we know now,
once you get the underlying immune defect,

19:37.009 --> 19:40.512
you do not recover from it,
which is a very, very important thing.

19:40.679 --> 19:43.348
FRANK SESNO:
<i>A small army of dedicated medical warriors</i>

19:43.432 --> 19:45.142
<i>is trying to combat this killer.</i>

19:45.559 --> 19:48.770
<i>In the laboratories,</i>
<i>researchers are scrambling for a cure.</i>

19:48.937 --> 19:51.231
<i>In the hospitals and doctors' offices,</i>

19:51.398 --> 19:53.901
<i>the front line soldiers</i>
<i>face a losing battle</i>

19:54.067 --> 19:57.196
<i>and must content themselves</i>
<i>with the little victories for now.</i>

19:58.906 --> 20:01.033
DR. FAUCI: <i>You know, every once in a while</i>
<i>when you're involved</i>

20:01.116 --> 20:03.160
<i>in a difficult situation you get bad news,</i>

20:03.285 --> 20:06.288
bad news and then sometimes
encouraging news comes along

20:06.413 --> 20:07.497
to make you feel a little better.

20:07.581 --> 20:10.584
It was all bad, bad, worse,
bad, worse, bad, worse.

20:13.253 --> 20:17.341
<i>It was just so unbelievably... frustrating</i>

20:17.883 --> 20:21.887
when you're used to...
being able to fix things

20:22.387 --> 20:25.057
and you're just not really fixing
anything.

20:26.725 --> 20:30.479
CHRISTINE: <i>It is very difficult to work</i>
<i>with young people who you care for,</i>

20:30.646 --> 20:34.775
become quite attached to
and in some cases even identify with

20:34.858 --> 20:38.820
and to watch them overtime
get sicker and die.

20:39.363 --> 20:43.867
It is not just one patient,
but one after another after another.

20:43.951 --> 20:48.705
And I had had jobs prior to this one
where people were very sick

20:49.164 --> 20:53.502
and many of my patients had died,
but this was different...

20:55.379 --> 20:59.800
because everybody was, sort of,
at the prime of their life.

21:03.303 --> 21:07.140
Back then, when you got sick
you were gone fast.

21:08.308 --> 21:11.186
Seven, eight, nine months
and it was horrible deaths.

21:14.815 --> 21:17.526
It was a time when all of us
were very scared

21:17.693 --> 21:20.862
and there was very little
that we could do.

21:22.906 --> 21:28.453
I found out in late '85, November 1985...

21:29.288 --> 21:30.414
<i>I was 24.</i>

21:30.998 --> 21:33.458
<i>I didn't know anything</i>
<i>about the politics of AIDS.</i>

21:33.583 --> 21:37.337
<i>I just knew that it was all of a sudden</i>
<i>this terrible scare story</i>

21:37.462 --> 21:42.134
and the country was in a panic about it
and that it was 100 percent fatal.

21:43.093 --> 21:45.887
ROBERT VAZQUEZ PACHECO:
<i>I was living in the Bronx</i>

21:45.971 --> 21:51.268
<i>with my lover Jeff, who was diagnosed</i>
<i>with Kaposi's sarcoma.</i>

21:51.810 --> 21:55.355
For me, the AIDS epidemic started then.

21:56.398 --> 22:00.610
MICHAEL MANGANIELLO:<i> I went to my doctor</i>
<i>and the minute he put the needle in my arm</i>

22:00.736 --> 22:04.281
I knew I was positive, I knew it.
And then I avoided his calls.

22:04.406 --> 22:07.784
For three and a half weeks,
I was able to avoid his calls...

22:08.410 --> 22:12.414
and then he found me and he said
that I was HIV positive.

22:12.664 --> 22:16.043
I said, "Well, what's the prognosis or..."

22:16.918 --> 22:18.628
He said, "18 months."

22:20.422 --> 22:22.215
Breathe in and out with your mouth open.

22:23.175 --> 22:26.887
DR. FAUCI:<i> You know, one of my patients</i>
<i>who had cytomegalovirus retinitis.</i>

22:27.346 --> 22:31.141
<i>Cytomegalovirus is a virus</i>
<i>that chews up the retina.</i>

22:32.434 --> 22:35.270
<i>And he was gradually losing vision.</i>

22:36.271 --> 22:38.648
He would walk in, he'd say,
"Dr. Fauci, how are you?"

22:38.815 --> 22:40.609
He was always upbeat. He'd walk in.

22:40.817 --> 22:42.861
I would smile. You know,
he'd make comments,

22:42.986 --> 22:45.030
"I love your smile.
You have a great smile."

22:45.322 --> 22:48.158
And I'd go in every day and morning,
afternoon, evening

22:48.241 --> 22:50.160
and then, one day,

22:50.369 --> 22:54.081
we walked in in the morning
and I walked in and went up to the desk

22:54.164 --> 22:56.041
and he said, "Who's there?"

22:56.583 --> 23:01.797
And it was clear, you know,
that he gone completely blind.

23:02.005 --> 23:03.590
And it was like... (GRUNTS)

23:04.257 --> 23:08.845
And we were standing around the bed
saying, "Now what?" you know?

23:09.012 --> 23:12.432
And it was... it was terrible,
because he lost his vision completely.

23:12.808 --> 23:13.975
Yeah.

23:14.434 --> 23:15.685
INTERVIEWER: It's affecting you now.

23:15.936 --> 23:17.479
-Yeah.
-INTERVIEWER: Why?

23:20.607 --> 23:22.275
(CRIES)

23:28.532 --> 23:32.202
(SNIFFS) Uh,
post-traumatic stress syndrome.

23:41.420 --> 23:42.546
That's what it is.

23:44.089 --> 23:50.220
(SOFT MELANCHOLIC MUSIC PLAYING)

23:51.847 --> 23:55.225
JENNY FAUCI: <i>My early understanding</i>
<i>of what my dad was doing was...</i>

23:55.767 --> 23:58.353
there's something happening
that's affecting people,

23:58.437 --> 24:00.272
that's hurting people,
that's killing people.

24:01.648 --> 24:05.902
<i>When I think about my dad growing up,</i>
<i>I certainly think about that seriousness,</i>

24:05.986 --> 24:10.365
that intensity and working hard
and wanting to do the right thing.

24:10.907 --> 24:12.117
<i>That's his compass.</i>

24:13.577 --> 24:18.415
<i>At the same time, I also think</i>
<i>about a person that I think</i>

24:18.540 --> 24:20.750
very few people get to see. (LAUGHS)

24:21.126 --> 24:24.629
<i>Which is someone who is funny</i>

24:24.713 --> 24:27.424
and weird and really playful.

24:28.133 --> 24:32.220
This is a record
for the month of July, 1988.

24:32.387 --> 24:34.598
We've been over 100,
so how many days in a row?

24:35.056 --> 24:36.308
-Several.
-CHRISTINE: Too many.

24:36.975 --> 24:40.187
Well, we're just sitting here
hanging out by the pool on a Sunday...

24:41.813 --> 24:42.939
Sunday morning.

24:44.107 --> 24:46.151
CHRISTINE:
Jenny and Daddy are gonna go swimming!

24:46.234 --> 24:47.819
Are you gonna go swimming?
Are you gonna show everybody

24:47.944 --> 24:49.779
how you could stay up straight
in the water?

24:50.739 --> 24:53.408
-Show Mommy.
-CHRISTINE: Come on.

24:54.534 --> 24:57.412
Yeah. You've got water in your eye?

24:57.537 --> 25:03.376
DR. FAUCI:<i> When Chris and I were knee deep</i>
<i>in responding to this historic pandemic.</i>

25:03.919 --> 25:07.756
<i>We wanted to and did raise a family.</i>

25:08.381 --> 25:09.966
-Now you've got us all?
-NAN: Yeah.

25:10.133 --> 25:11.551
-Okay, Nan.
-(LAUGHS)

25:12.260 --> 25:13.970
-Here we are.
-Here we are.

25:14.346 --> 25:17.432
Here's Jenny and her baby sister.
Jennifer, Mommy, and Daddy.

25:17.557 --> 25:19.100
Jennifer and her baby sister Megan.

25:19.184 --> 25:20.352
DR. FAUCI: Hi, Megan.

25:20.435 --> 25:22.229
-Oh, don't you look pretty!
-CHRISTINE: Look, it's coming off.

25:22.312 --> 25:27.400
DR. FAUCI: It's March 30th, 1989...

25:28.401 --> 25:30.487
and Megan is getting herself a bath.

25:31.404 --> 25:34.157
DR. FAUCI:<i> Jenny first and Megan,</i>
<i>then Alison.</i>

25:34.407 --> 25:36.535
-Hi, Momma.
-CHRISTINE: Are you the audience with me?

25:36.660 --> 25:37.661
Yes.

25:37.744 --> 25:39.788
-CHRISTINE: Merry Christmas.
-(SCREAMS)

25:39.913 --> 25:42.374
CHRISTINE: (LAUGHS) Whoa, don't fall!

25:42.499 --> 25:43.708
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

25:43.875 --> 25:46.628
January seventh, the blizzard of 1996.

25:46.711 --> 25:49.714
Probably the largest snow storm
in the history of Washington, D.C...

25:49.965 --> 25:53.301
A foot. It's a foot
and it's gonna be two feet.

25:55.262 --> 25:58.807
When our children were little,
he used to work all the time.

25:59.391 --> 26:02.561
And there were times
when they wouldn't see him

26:02.727 --> 26:04.604
for a couple of days sometimes.

26:05.855 --> 26:08.525
DR. FAUCI:<i> I wouldn't say I neglected</i>
<i>the raising of the children,</i>

26:08.650 --> 26:13.780
but I did not sacrifice
professional things...

26:14.781 --> 26:16.324
as much as maybe I should have.

26:16.616 --> 26:17.742
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

26:17.826 --> 26:21.871
DR. FAUCI: <i>I was not going</i>
<i>to every soccer match,</i>

26:21.955 --> 26:25.792
<i>every track meet, every swim meet.</i>

26:26.585 --> 26:28.587
-Yes.
-CHRISTINE: Whoo! Yeah.

26:29.504 --> 26:31.548
DR. FAUCI: <i>Chris did everything.</i>

26:32.882 --> 26:37.512
<i>But we did something that I think</i>
<i>physically is a little unhealthy,</i>

26:37.846 --> 26:41.224
I don't recommend it for people,
but it worked.

26:41.725 --> 26:43.977
We decided that
we were gonna have dinner...

26:44.853 --> 26:49.149
together every night
no matter how late the dinner was.

26:51.151 --> 26:55.405
JENNY:<i> He would come home</i>
<i>from like a 12 or 13-hour day of work</i>

26:55.655 --> 26:59.117
and he would come in the kitchen
and start dancing with my mom.

26:59.367 --> 27:03.872
I'm like, "Dad, we want to eat dinner.
Please come and sit down."

27:05.665 --> 27:10.712
But we understood that when he's working,
which is all of the time,

27:10.795 --> 27:13.340
he's laser focused.

27:17.177 --> 27:19.012
DR. FAUCI:<i> Rather than name</i>
<i>each and every one of these,</i>

27:19.095 --> 27:21.306
why don't I just talk
about asthma analogy,

27:21.431 --> 27:25.977
I'll mention transportation, autoimmunity,
vaccine developments, skip cancer,

27:26.102 --> 27:28.271
go to immune mediated disease
and then end up with AIDS.

27:28.480 --> 27:32.400
PETER THOMAS: <i>AIDS brings a new level</i>
<i>of pressure and public attention to NIH,</i>

27:32.651 --> 27:34.569
<i>and especially to Dr. Fauci,</i>

27:34.694 --> 27:38.031
<i>who already manages</i>
<i>three full time jobs at NIH.</i>

27:38.114 --> 27:41.451
<i>Administrator, physician,</i>
<i>research scientist.</i>

27:41.701 --> 27:44.162
Pardon my eating,
I'm having my lunch before the hearing,

27:44.245 --> 27:46.665
so if I'm eating in your ear,
don't worry.

27:46.748 --> 27:49.250
We don't have the answer.
We're trying to get the answer,

27:49.376 --> 27:52.796
but we're letting the science take us
where it's taking us.

27:53.088 --> 27:54.589
Researchers believe that they have made

27:54.673 --> 27:57.300
a monumental breakthrough
in the fight against AIDS.

27:57.384 --> 28:00.512
The deadly disease that attacks
the body's immune system.

28:00.804 --> 28:03.098
US Government scientists announced
in Washington today,

28:03.181 --> 28:06.184
they have isolated a virus
they believe causes AIDS.

28:06.309 --> 28:09.354
<i>The breakthrough came</i>
<i>at the National Institutes of Health,</i>

28:09.521 --> 28:12.107
<i>where a way was found</i>
<i>to mass produce the AIDS virus,</i>

28:12.524 --> 28:15.735
<i>study it and most importantly,</i>
<i>to test blood for it.</i>

28:16.236 --> 28:18.655
-REPORTER: Fauci?
-DR. FAUCI: F-A-U-C-I.

28:18.822 --> 28:22.742
DR. FAUCI: <i>We found that we had a virus.</i>
<i>It was really quite transforming.</i>

28:23.118 --> 28:25.829
Now I have it in my hand,
I know what the hell it is.

28:25.995 --> 28:29.624
You know, I have it in a test tube.
It's not like this thing

28:29.708 --> 28:31.793
that's floating around
that we have no idea what it is.

28:33.545 --> 28:35.630
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

28:36.214 --> 28:39.843
(ABULANCE SIREN WAILING)

28:43.054 --> 28:48.518
There is an inherent fear...
built into viruses.

28:49.561 --> 28:51.104
MIGUEL ALMAGUER:
<i>The lives of millions of Americans</i>

28:51.271 --> 28:54.441
<i>are being severely disrupted</i>
<i>by the coronavirus pandemic.</i>

28:54.899 --> 28:58.945
<i>Schools, work, even iconic institutions</i>
<i>like Broadway and Disneyworld</i>

28:59.028 --> 29:00.905
<i>are shut down. Experts say...</i>

29:01.531 --> 29:04.242
When we hear about one
that is taking off...

29:04.784 --> 29:07.287
it really rings all of the alarm bells.

29:09.247 --> 29:11.291
DR. FAUCI: <i>Seeing a vibrant city</i>
<i>like New York</i>

29:11.583 --> 29:17.005
resembling a bit of a ghost town
was a moving... feeling for me.

29:17.088 --> 29:18.923
-Very emotional...
-(AMBULANCE SIREN WAILING)

29:19.048 --> 29:22.927
<i>...because, you know, I grew up as a kid</i>
<i>roaming around Manhattan.</i>

29:23.011 --> 29:26.097
<i>And to see it empty</i>
<i>was just very, very shocking</i>

29:26.181 --> 29:27.182
<i>in many respects.</i>

29:28.099 --> 29:30.185
<i>But community spread was rampant</i>

29:30.518 --> 29:33.563
<i>and we had to make a decision</i>
<i>to shut everything down.</i>

29:34.230 --> 29:35.774
GABE GUTIERREZ:
<i>The tri-state region now topping</i>

29:35.857 --> 29:40.820
<i>90,000 confirmed cases of COVID-19</i>
<i>and more than 1,500 deaths.</i>

29:40.945 --> 29:43.698
JOHN BERMAN:<i> Hospitals are reeling</i>
<i>with New York City's mayor,</i>

29:43.907 --> 29:46.659
<i>warning they will run out of supplies</i>
<i>by this weekend.</i>

29:49.913 --> 29:51.498
DR. FAUCI: Okay. VRC.

29:51.873 --> 29:52.874
MALE VOICE: Sure.

29:56.211 --> 29:57.796
DR. FAUCI: <i>As soon as we heard</i>

29:58.379 --> 30:02.675
<i>that in Wuhan these cases</i>
<i>apparently appeared,</i>

30:02.926 --> 30:06.262
we had no idea
if it was gonna turn out to be bad.

30:06.346 --> 30:10.892
We just knew it is conceivable
that this could turn out to be a pandemic.

30:11.893 --> 30:15.438
<i>My group here</i>
<i>in the Vaccine Research Center said...</i>

30:16.439 --> 30:20.318
"As soon as we get a sequence,
let's go for it."

30:21.277 --> 30:23.404
<i>The sequence came out,</i>
<i>I believe, on the ninth.</i>

30:23.530 --> 30:25.949
<i>We had the meeting on the tenth.</i>
<i>By the time we got to the 15th,</i>

30:26.199 --> 30:28.284
we were already in the process
of making it

30:28.368 --> 30:32.247
and then 63, 65 days later,
we were in a phase one trial.

30:32.413 --> 30:36.626
Scientists all across the world
are now racing to find a vaccine

30:36.751 --> 30:39.254
that can help combat
the coronavirus in the future.

30:39.337 --> 30:41.089
DAVID SPUNT:
<i>The National Institutes of Health</i>

30:41.172 --> 30:42.799
<i>and a Massachusetts company Moderna</i>

30:42.882 --> 30:45.260
<i>are behind the record speed</i>
<i>clinical trials.</i>

30:45.426 --> 30:47.554
We've been hearing a lot
about the Moderna vaccine,

30:47.637 --> 30:49.055
that's an mRNA vaccine.

30:49.138 --> 30:50.807
ALISYN:
<i>This is different from other vaccines.</i>

30:50.890 --> 30:54.018
<i>It uses mRNA to basically teach the body</i>
<i>how to fight the virus.</i>

30:54.102 --> 30:57.355
<i>But never before have we seen</i>
<i>a successful mRNA vaccine.</i>

30:57.856 --> 30:59.983
When we were confronted with this virus,

31:00.316 --> 31:04.153
there are a lot of very smart people
at the NIH who put their heads together

31:04.487 --> 31:08.157
and realized that mRNA vaccines
could be a real option.

31:08.241 --> 31:11.995
SANJAY GUPTA:<i> If it works,</i>
<i>it's a potentially safer and faster path.</i>

31:12.370 --> 31:16.040
<i>Shortening the development process</i>
<i>from decades to years.</i>

31:16.124 --> 31:19.627
Even though we didn't all know about it,
there was a lot of research being done

31:19.711 --> 31:24.090
<i>for many, many years with the NIH</i>
<i>towards making mRNA vaccines.</i>

31:24.632 --> 31:26.968
-DR. FAUCI: I think it's gonna work.
-MALE VOICE: I do too.

31:27.051 --> 31:28.219
I mean, I really do.

31:29.345 --> 31:33.349
We had been priming
the pump for years before

31:33.683 --> 31:36.936
with the platform technology,
in this case mRNA.

31:37.395 --> 31:41.232
<i>So, as soon as we found out that we were</i>
<i>dealing with a brand new virus,</i>

31:41.399 --> 31:46.988
we said, "This what we do.
We make vaccines. Let's do it."

31:47.071 --> 31:50.575
This is a very exciting technology
at the mRNA vaccines

31:50.867 --> 31:52.118
and it's extremely exciting,

31:52.201 --> 31:54.787
but I don't believe a single one of them
has ever reached market.

31:56.497 --> 31:58.458
APOORVA MANDAVILLI:
<i>It's incredibly impressive</i>

31:58.583 --> 32:01.711
<i>that they made that call,</i>
<i>because it's a bold one.</i>

32:02.128 --> 32:06.382
It took some amount of courage
to move forward with something

32:06.466 --> 32:08.551
that you know isn't an absolute certainty.

32:08.760 --> 32:10.720
I talked to Tony Fauci yesterday,

32:10.803 --> 32:13.306
the Head of the National Institute
of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.

32:13.473 --> 32:16.309
A vaccine is in the works,
but it's a couple of years away.

32:16.559 --> 32:19.729
The fastest we had ever developed
a vaccine before that was for mumps

32:19.812 --> 32:20.855
and that took four years.

32:20.939 --> 32:22.732
And so, we're able to move
very, very fast,

32:22.857 --> 32:26.235
so as soon as we get the phase one dose
out of the NIH,

32:26.527 --> 32:28.196
we'll be able to start phase two
right away.

32:28.446 --> 32:31.157
You're talking over the next few months
you think you could have a vaccine?

32:31.240 --> 32:32.992
-Correct.
-With phase two.

32:33.701 --> 32:37.330
Yeah. You won't have a vaccine.
You'll have a vaccine to go into testing.

32:37.538 --> 32:38.581
MALE VOICE: Testing, yes.

32:39.248 --> 32:42.418
Well, you have the greatest companies
in the world sitting around the table.

32:42.502 --> 32:45.838
I mean, Johnson & Johnson and Pfizer
and all of the companies. Gilead.

32:46.214 --> 32:49.217
Uh, you have all of these great companies
and that's what they're saying,

32:49.384 --> 32:50.802
so I think that...

32:51.052 --> 32:53.846
DR. FAUCI: Would you make sure you get
the President the information

32:53.930 --> 32:57.850
that a vaccine that you make
and start testing in a year

32:57.934 --> 32:59.811
is not a vaccine that's deployable.

33:00.061 --> 33:03.481
So, he's asking the question
"When is it gonna be deployable?"

33:03.815 --> 33:07.610
and that is gonna be, at the earliest,
a year to a year and half,

33:07.694 --> 33:09.320
no matter how fast you go.

33:09.654 --> 33:13.408
I met with the President and with Tony
and a few others in the room

33:13.491 --> 33:14.575
on a couple of occasions.

33:15.702 --> 33:19.789
<i>Oftentimes it was Tony</i>
<i>who was seen as the main proponent</i>

33:19.872 --> 33:21.374
<i>of the unpopular view.</i>

33:21.457 --> 33:25.211
You take a solid flu vaccine,
you don't think that would have an impact

33:25.294 --> 33:27.171
or much of an impact on corona?

33:27.338 --> 33:28.923
DR. FAUCI: No, no. Probably not.

33:29.966 --> 33:33.177
INTERVIEWER: Can you talk
about your early meetings

33:33.261 --> 33:36.347
with the President
and your impressions of him?

33:36.597 --> 33:38.141
Is that something
that you're willing to share?

33:38.808 --> 33:39.809
Yikes!

33:41.561 --> 33:44.022
How deep do you want to get? (LAUGHS)

33:44.313 --> 33:49.193
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

33:49.861 --> 33:54.699
DR. FAUCI: <i>We had task force meetings</i>
<i>very regularly.</i>

33:54.907 --> 33:58.619
First, a few times a week and then,
almost literally every single day.

33:59.996 --> 34:03.207
MALE REPORTER: <i>We're live now</i>
<i>at the White House in the briefing room,</i>

34:03.332 --> 34:06.085
<i>where moments from now President Trump</i>
<i>will hold a news conference</i>

34:06.252 --> 34:08.504
<i>talking about</i>
<i>his administration's response</i>

34:08.588 --> 34:10.506
<i>to the coronavirus outbreak.</i>

34:10.590 --> 34:12.675
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

34:12.800 --> 34:17.805
DR. FAUCI: <i>We had press conferences</i>
<i>that were a hybrid of a press conference.</i>

34:17.930 --> 34:21.017
<i>It wasn't totally dominated</i>
<i>by the scientists.</i>

34:21.601 --> 34:22.685
Thank you very much.

34:22.769 --> 34:25.229
DR. FAUCI:<i> The President would get up</i>
<i>with his style</i>

34:25.772 --> 34:29.484
and... for reasons that none of us
could understand,

34:29.567 --> 34:33.029
it was always confronting the press.

34:33.196 --> 34:36.449
What do you say to Americans
who are watching right now who are scared?

34:36.657 --> 34:40.453
I say that you're a terrible reporter.
That's what I say. Go ahead.

34:40.661 --> 34:42.789
DR. FAUCI:<i> Because of that,</i>
<i>the public health messages</i>

34:43.122 --> 34:44.582
<i>got a bit muddled.</i>

34:45.249 --> 34:48.961
The President might get up,
and out of nowhere, say something

34:49.420 --> 34:51.881
that we would all go,
"What's that all about?"

34:51.964 --> 34:54.634
JAKE TAPPER: <i>President Trump's</i>
<i>been touting an anti-malaria drug</i>

34:54.717 --> 34:56.719
that he says
could help treat the coronavirus.

34:56.803 --> 34:59.055
So, how beneficial is hydroxychloroquine?

34:59.180 --> 35:02.725
My next guest says doctors
are already using this treatment

35:02.809 --> 35:04.519
in the United States successfully.

35:04.602 --> 35:09.023
For me, I'm absolutely convinced
this is what saved my life.

35:09.107 --> 35:12.819
It was the typical example
that we scientists shudder at.

35:12.985 --> 35:18.366
Joe Jones tells you that I did this
and I got better, therefore, it works.

35:18.991 --> 35:22.537
And it was very clear
that there was no evidence whatsoever

35:22.787 --> 35:25.623
that hydroxychloroquine... worked.

35:26.207 --> 35:29.043
And that's when things got complicated.

35:29.210 --> 35:30.086
Yes, John.

35:30.461 --> 35:33.047
JOHN ROBERTS: A question
for Dr. Fauci, if I could.

35:33.172 --> 35:36.717
Dr. Fauci, it was explained yesterday
there has been some promise

35:36.801 --> 35:38.344
with hydroxychloroquine,

35:38.427 --> 35:41.806
this potential therapy for people
who are infected with coronavirus.

35:42.098 --> 35:45.518
Is there any evidence to suggest
that, as with malaria,

35:45.601 --> 35:48.104
it might be used as a prophylaxis
against COVID-19?

35:48.271 --> 35:52.650
No. The answer is no and the evidence
that you're talking about, John,

35:52.733 --> 35:54.235
is anecdotal evidence.

35:54.318 --> 35:58.114
That was the first time that publicly,
with all the cameras rolling,

35:58.322 --> 36:02.326
I just had to get up and contradict him.

36:02.827 --> 36:05.538
But the information
that you are referring to specifically

36:05.663 --> 36:08.833
is anecdotal. It was not done
in a controlled clinical trial,

36:08.958 --> 36:11.377
so you really can't make
any definitive statement about it.

36:12.795 --> 36:14.630
DR. FAUCI: <i>When I stepped back</i>
<i>from the podium,</i>

36:14.714 --> 36:21.387
I remembered the advice that I got
decades earlier by my good friend

36:21.470 --> 36:26.809
who said, "Whenever you go
into the White House, you should assume

36:26.893 --> 36:30.104
"that there's a possibility
that you're not gonna get asked back,

36:30.521 --> 36:34.066
because you might have to tell somebody
something they didn't want to hear."

36:34.233 --> 36:37.820
And as I stepped back I said,
"Well, this may be it."

36:38.112 --> 36:40.740
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

36:40.823 --> 36:44.994
I think... (CLEARS THROAT)
...without saying too much,

36:45.119 --> 36:50.458
I'm probably more of a fan of that
than... maybe than anybody.

36:50.750 --> 36:54.921
He was so much in his own world
that... I don't...

36:55.004 --> 36:57.924
He didn't react in a way of saying

36:58.049 --> 37:00.259
how dare you contradict me
I'm the President?

37:00.384 --> 37:03.012
It was like, I'll say what I'm gonna say,
you say what you're gonna say.

37:03.387 --> 37:06.682
Let's see if it works.
It might and it might not.

37:06.807 --> 37:09.393
I happen to feel good about it,
but who knows?

37:09.518 --> 37:12.104
I've been right a lot.
Let's see what happens.

37:12.188 --> 37:13.564
-John.
-JOHN: Can I come back to the science

37:13.648 --> 37:15.316
-and the logistics?
-You ought to be ashamed of yourself.

37:15.399 --> 37:17.944
JOHN: <i>The units that were ordered,</i>
<i>are they for...</i>

37:21.239 --> 37:23.824
SANJAY:<i> It just was</i>
<i>a remarkable sort of back and forth</i>

37:23.908 --> 37:26.661
between someone who's using
their gut instincts,

37:26.744 --> 37:29.247
not scientifically based,
not evidence based

37:29.497 --> 37:32.208
against, you know,
a venerable scientist who kept

37:32.500 --> 37:36.671
sort of, on the fly, it seems,
trying to fact check the President.

37:39.840 --> 37:41.550
<i>I just had never seen anything like it.</i>

37:41.634 --> 37:45.388
<i>I think Tony Fauci probably has one</i>
<i>of the hardest jobs in America right now.</i>

37:48.099 --> 37:50.434
(KEYBOARD KEYS CLATTERING)

37:50.726 --> 37:55.106
Communication is not ancillary
to fighting an epidemic.

37:55.439 --> 37:58.150
Communication is central
to fighting an epidemic.

37:58.526 --> 38:02.697
I'd like to provide some basic
but important facts about Ebola

38:02.905 --> 38:04.115
and its transmission.

38:04.282 --> 38:07.076
SUSAN RICE:<i> During the crises</i>
<i>that we faced in the Obama Administration,</i>

38:07.201 --> 38:11.914
it was particularly Dr. Fauci
who brought this extraordinary sobriety...

38:12.498 --> 38:18.087
and rationality and fact based,
evidence based leadership to the table.

38:18.212 --> 38:21.966
-(AMBULANCE SIREN WAILING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

38:26.387 --> 38:28.264
MATT LAUER:
<i>The Centers for Disease Control</i>

38:28.347 --> 38:32.143
<i>is closely monitoring what's become</i>
<i>the largest Ebola outbreak in history.</i>

38:32.310 --> 38:35.187
NANCY SNYDERMAN:<i> Ebola has been</i>
<i>ravaging West Africa since March</i>

38:35.313 --> 38:38.524
<i>and shocked disease specialists</i>
<i>when it hopped a border by plane.</i>

38:39.984 --> 38:43.279
TOM FRIEDEN: <i>The moment Ebola</i>
<i>began spreading in cities,</i>

38:43.821 --> 38:45.740
we were at the edge of an abyss.

38:46.407 --> 38:48.242
TOM COSTELLO:<i> From the front lines</i>
<i>of West Africa</i>

38:48.367 --> 38:52.621
<i>to the front door of America,</i>
<i>an all-out push to get ahead of Ebola.</i>

38:52.955 --> 38:55.374
I think we've got to let
the science guide us.

38:57.043 --> 38:58.461
SEAN HANNITY: <i>The outbreak</i>
<i>that the President said</i>

38:58.586 --> 39:00.838
<i>was unlikely to come here is now here.</i>

39:02.882 --> 39:07.887
FRANCIS COLLINS: <i>Our nation</i>
<i>was really wired into a frenzy of anxiety</i>

39:07.970 --> 39:10.890
about whether this
is gonna sweep across the country

39:11.098 --> 39:12.433
and take us all with it.

39:12.516 --> 39:16.228
Right now we have a devastating epidemic
in West Africa

39:16.312 --> 39:18.731
and we're having an epidemic of fear
in the United States,

39:18.856 --> 39:21.192
so we've got to continue to try
and educate people

39:21.275 --> 39:23.986
about what they need to
or do not need to be afraid of.

39:24.111 --> 39:28.783
Dr. Fauci clearly understood
and clearly conveyed

39:29.200 --> 39:32.578
that there was a wise,
scientifically driven way

39:32.661 --> 39:35.498
to deal with this and a hysterical way
to deal with it.

39:35.831 --> 39:39.251
The reason we are having
this very difficult situation

39:39.418 --> 39:41.003
in the African countries

39:41.087 --> 39:45.132
is because they don't have the system
to be able to contain it.

39:45.299 --> 39:48.052
If they had the system,
we would not be seeing

39:48.177 --> 39:50.054
all of this suffering and dying
in West Africa.

39:50.262 --> 39:53.599
If that's the case and if it's one case
in the United States now,

39:53.682 --> 39:54.725
as we know it is...

39:55.643 --> 39:57.561
why are we having
news conferences like this

39:57.686 --> 39:58.979
and why are we all so afraid?

39:59.397 --> 40:01.941
SUSAN: <i>Ebola is a terrifying virus.</i>

40:02.066 --> 40:05.611
<i>It causes you to bleed</i>
<i>through your orifices.</i>

40:06.278 --> 40:09.824
<i>It's transmissible through bodily fluids.</i>

40:10.074 --> 40:15.287
It's not, therefore as easy to catch
as a COVID-19 or a flu virus

40:15.413 --> 40:16.705
because it's not airborne.

40:17.331 --> 40:19.166
<i>But it is much more deadly.</i>

40:22.878 --> 40:26.632
The American part of dealing
with Ebola here in this country

40:27.007 --> 40:29.301
took basically a 90 degree turn
this weekend.

40:29.885 --> 40:32.721
MALE REPOTER: <i>A nurse in Dallas</i>
<i>becomes the first person</i>

40:32.847 --> 40:35.599
<i>to contract Ebola in the United States.</i>

40:35.724 --> 40:40.271
Just moments ago, Nurse Nina Pham
left the city for an NIH facility.

40:40.396 --> 40:42.481
DON LEMON: <i>I believe that it's Nina Pham.</i>

40:42.606 --> 40:44.859
SANJAY:<i> It looks like</i>
<i>she's walking off the plane there, Don.</i>

40:44.984 --> 40:47.445
-DON: <i>Yeah, very slowly.</i>
-When we were called upon...

40:48.028 --> 40:52.116
to care for one of the nurses
who got infected, Tony led that charge.

40:52.241 --> 40:56.412
She came here at 11:54.
All of us have been up all night.

40:56.620 --> 40:58.456
We haven't learned a lot
about the virus yet.

40:58.581 --> 41:00.082
We're taking care of the patient.

41:00.291 --> 41:03.419
DR. FAUCI: <i>Even some of our staff</i>
<i>and our community</i>

41:03.919 --> 41:07.631
were a little reluctant
to go near the doctors and the nurses

41:08.090 --> 41:11.302
who were taking care of Ebola patients
because they thought

41:11.385 --> 41:13.762
we were going to infect people
in the community,

41:13.929 --> 41:16.056
which was impossible.
That was not gonna happen.

41:17.725 --> 41:20.060
<i>So, when Nina completely recovered,</i>

41:20.144 --> 41:22.730
<i>we decided</i>
<i>we would publicly discharge her.</i>

41:23.564 --> 41:26.358
<i>As we were waiting in the lobby,</i>
<i>I was saying,</i>

41:26.525 --> 41:31.822
"Maybe I should do something here
that could change around the stigma."

41:31.906 --> 41:36.368
Our patient Nina Pham is free of Ebola.

41:36.577 --> 41:37.578
Nina?

41:37.703 --> 41:43.209
(CROWD APPLAUDS, CHEERS)

41:43.417 --> 41:44.919
DR. FAUCI: <i>I wanted people to see</i>

41:45.127 --> 41:50.174
that I was not afraid of hugging someone
who was completely recovered.

41:51.550 --> 41:54.553
<i>I mean, it was, like, click, click,</i>
<i>click, click all over the place.</i>

41:54.762 --> 41:56.514
-MALE REPORTER 20: We love you, Nina.
-FEMALE VOICE 2: Yeah.

41:58.849 --> 42:01.352
FRANCIS: <i>To be able to turn</i>
<i>that around and say,</i>

42:01.519 --> 42:04.313
"Here's somebody who had it
and she's fine,"

42:04.605 --> 42:08.984
it's a counter to that visceral fear
of contagion.

42:09.109 --> 42:11.570
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

42:11.904 --> 42:14.532
LAURIE GARRETT: <i>Tony has an ability</i>
<i>to deal with fear</i>

42:14.782 --> 42:17.201
<i>and a really serious understanding</i>

42:17.284 --> 42:21.914
of how to speak about... uncertainty

42:22.373 --> 42:27.545
and threat...
to a terrified general population.

42:28.379 --> 42:32.508
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

42:32.591 --> 42:35.427
The AIDS problem in America
is only getting worse

42:35.511 --> 42:37.471
with every passing day
and there is no sign

42:37.596 --> 42:39.181
that it will get better any time soon.

42:40.182 --> 42:41.600
MALE REPORTER:
<i>The National Academy of Sciences</i>

42:41.684 --> 42:43.477
<i>is warning of an AIDS catastrophe</i>

42:43.561 --> 42:47.147
<i>unless the government is willing to spend</i>
<i>big money for education and research.</i>

42:47.940 --> 42:51.902
Had this disease afflicted children
or members of the chamber of commerce,

42:52.194 --> 42:54.697
I'm sure the Reagan Administration
would have been breaking down

42:54.822 --> 42:56.448
all doors in order to deal with it.

42:57.074 --> 43:00.953
As the numbers increase,
so does something else. Fear.

43:01.328 --> 43:02.621
-(PHONE RINGING)
-The AIDS hotline.

43:02.705 --> 43:04.331
FEMALE REPORTER:
<i>Most of the callers besieging</i>

43:04.415 --> 43:07.376
<i>the country's AIDS hotlines</i>
<i>are heterosexuals,</i>

43:07.543 --> 43:10.963
<i>panicked at the realization</i>
<i>that they too could be at risk.</i>

43:11.422 --> 43:16.302
I personally will tell my child
if someone has AIDS, stay away from them.

43:17.386 --> 43:18.679
DR. FAUCI:<i> At the time,</i>

43:18.762 --> 43:22.099
<i>people were very concerned</i>
<i>about transmission.</i>

43:22.600 --> 43:26.353
We knew how this was transmitted,
but there was still this crazy stigma.

43:27.938 --> 43:31.567
<i>Even though I was a researcher</i>
<i>and a physician scientist,</i>

43:31.734 --> 43:34.194
<i>I really wanted to get out</i>
<i>and address that.</i>

43:34.903 --> 43:37.489
MALE REPORTER 2:<i> One of the nation's</i>
<i>outstanding researchers on AIDS</i>

43:37.823 --> 43:39.241
<i>is Dr. Anthony Fauci.</i>

43:39.366 --> 43:41.744
Dr. Fauci, thank you very much
for coming in today.

43:41.910 --> 43:45.247
PHIL DONAHUE: Anthony Fauci, MD,
National Institute of Health,

43:45.331 --> 43:47.916
make us feel better
about these anxieties.

43:48.292 --> 43:53.339
It appears that the transmissibility
of AIDS is through repeated sexual contact

43:53.672 --> 43:56.508
and/or in IV drug users
in sharing needles.

43:56.759 --> 44:00.846
There is absolutely no evidence at all
that AIDS can be transmitted

44:01.055 --> 44:03.974
by casual contact, by touching,

44:04.058 --> 44:07.478
by any kind of normal social interactions
that you might have with anyone.

44:07.936 --> 44:11.482
So, I think that the fears
may be understandable,

44:11.732 --> 44:13.525
but they're not scientifically sound.

44:13.901 --> 44:16.904
DR. FAUCI: <i>One of the issues</i>
<i>I had to push back against</i>

44:16.987 --> 44:19.948
is that this was kind
of somebody else's disease.

44:20.282 --> 44:22.076
FEMALE VOICE: Do you think
that maybe the guilt

44:22.159 --> 44:24.453
that the gay community
has been dealing with

44:24.536 --> 44:27.122
could be a reason
for the breakdown of the immune system?

44:27.331 --> 44:28.290
No.

44:28.415 --> 44:32.044
What is your response to those who say
only a small, unsavory group of people

44:32.127 --> 44:33.253
is affected by it?

44:33.337 --> 44:36.382
Therefore, it is not something that those
who lead the straight and narrow life

44:36.465 --> 44:38.050
should be as concerned about there.

44:38.133 --> 44:40.386
To say because someone has
a particular lifestyle

44:40.469 --> 44:43.055
that they're unsavory,
I think is objectionable.

44:43.972 --> 44:45.641
These individuals who are infected,

44:45.724 --> 44:48.394
be they homosexuals
or IV drug abusers, are people.

44:48.477 --> 44:52.731
People who deserve compassion,
who deserve care and who deserve concern.

44:52.940 --> 44:56.568
We need to distinguish
between unfair discrimination

44:56.652 --> 44:59.029
-and fair discrimination.
-AUDIENCE: Oh!

44:59.154 --> 45:03.617
And they are reservoir
of a host of contagious diseases.

45:03.701 --> 45:06.036
I'm gonna have to remove the mic
and we'll move on down this way.

45:06.161 --> 45:07.830
In the light
of that extraordinary outburst,

45:07.913 --> 45:09.832
