59:00.828 --> 59:04.040
Tony Fauci was... the enemy.

59:09.963 --> 59:14.259
For me, I had just lost my partner.
I was...

59:14.968 --> 59:20.139
in grief and we needed drugs.
We needed them yesterday.

59:20.306 --> 59:23.810
ACT UP's focus
was always drugs into bodies.

59:23.893 --> 59:25.645
That's what the motto was.

59:28.147 --> 59:29.524
<i>Make sure that</i>
<i>we could find treatment</i>

59:29.649 --> 59:31.442
<i>for HIV and AIDS for people</i>

59:31.651 --> 59:33.945
<i>and make sure that it was accessible</i>
<i>to everyone.</i>

59:35.280 --> 59:39.242
AIDS patients breaking the law,
in a desperate battle

59:39.367 --> 59:40.660
to save their own lives.

59:40.785 --> 59:42.453
TOM JARRIEL:
<i>Many are now treating themselves</i>

59:42.579 --> 59:45.039
<i>with medications not yet approved</i>
<i>by the government.</i>

59:46.457 --> 59:50.336
DAVID:<i> We were fighting with the FDA</i>
<i>over access to an experimental drug</i>

59:50.628 --> 59:54.215
to treat the pneumonia
that was the leading cause of death

59:54.465 --> 59:56.134
amongst people with AIDS.

59:56.301 --> 59:59.262
It was an approved drug already
for cancer patients

59:59.345 --> 1:00:02.015
<i>that had immune suppression</i>
<i>and it worked for them.</i>

1:00:03.433 --> 1:00:08.313
And Tony said "No,
we're not really interested in that.

1:00:09.022 --> 1:00:11.149
<i>"We're interested in this drug AZT</i>

1:00:11.232 --> 1:00:13.443
<i>and that's where we're gonna put</i>
<i>our resources."</i>

1:00:14.402 --> 1:00:16.696
PETER:<i> About a year later,</i>

1:00:17.280 --> 1:00:23.369
I think 16 or 18,000 people with AIDS
died of PCP pneumonia.

1:00:24.120 --> 1:00:27.165
And we accused him
of causing those deaths.

1:00:28.374 --> 1:00:31.711
LARRY: <i>This government isn't equipped</i>
<i>to put 10,000 people into a trial.</i>

1:00:31.836 --> 1:00:32.837
<i>It is so disorganized.</i>

1:00:32.920 --> 1:00:34.505
HOST:
<i>There are so many committees.</i>

1:00:34.589 --> 1:00:35.923
<i>But it could be equipped.</i>

1:00:36.007 --> 1:00:37.842
If Tony Fauci were courageous enough
to whisper...

1:00:37.925 --> 1:00:39.427
<i>I want to stay away from the politics.</i>

1:00:39.510 --> 1:00:42.639
...in President Bush's ear
let's do something about this plague.

1:00:42.889 --> 1:00:49.187
It was a little confusing because I,
who had been knocking myself out,

1:00:49.771 --> 1:00:55.485
trying to do the right thing,
was the object of the anger.

1:00:55.693 --> 1:00:58.112
(VOILIN PLAYING)

1:00:58.321 --> 1:01:02.033
DR. FAUCI:<i> But then something happened</i>
<i>within me and I said,</i>

1:01:02.784 --> 1:01:06.079
"You know, something's going on
that I'm missing here."

1:01:09.290 --> 1:01:13.670
<i>And that's when I started</i>
<i>to really reach out.</i>

1:01:13.836 --> 1:01:15.546
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1:01:15.672 --> 1:01:17.799
PETER: <i>It was pretty much the first</i>
<i>and only time, I think,</i>

1:01:17.882 --> 1:01:23.096
in ACT UP's early history
where anybody in government came to us.

1:01:23.596 --> 1:01:25.348
ACT UP REP 1:

1:01:26.349 --> 1:01:29.644
DAVID:<i> We invited him to come</i>
<i>to an ACT UP meeting.</i>

1:01:30.019 --> 1:01:35.692
He knew that he was gonna face an audience
that was hostile and distrustful.

1:01:36.109 --> 1:01:38.736
ACT UP MEMBER 1:

1:01:54.794 --> 1:01:58.965
DR. FAUCI:<i> It was quite a scene.</i>
<i>I went up there to listen to them</i>

1:01:59.173 --> 1:02:01.759
and to try and explain to them
the rationale

1:02:01.926 --> 1:02:05.847
for why we were doing what we were doing,
even though they did not agree.

1:02:06.347 --> 1:02:09.016
ACT UP MEMBER 2:

1:02:14.814 --> 1:02:15.898
DR. FAUCI:

1:02:21.863 --> 1:02:26.117
The criticism, the hostility,
it didn't really seem to phase him.

1:02:42.216 --> 1:02:46.095
My first impression
was that we're dealing with Brooklyn here.

1:02:46.804 --> 1:02:50.516
<i>He got a complete grilling</i>
<i>and continued the conversation.</i>

1:02:50.808 --> 1:02:52.852
DR FAUCI:

1:03:01.944 --> 1:03:04.113
DR. FAUCI: <i>We didn't agree on everything</i>
<i>in that first meeting,</i>

1:03:04.197 --> 1:03:06.365
<i>but their instincts were right.</i>

1:03:08.993 --> 1:03:13.456
<i>And that started a series of dialogs</i>

1:03:14.081 --> 1:03:18.169
that did not stop the demonstrations.

1:03:18.419 --> 1:03:22.048
CROWD: It's a lie, it's a sham,
it won't work!

1:03:22.256 --> 1:03:23.883
It's a lie, it's a sham!

1:03:24.050 --> 1:03:25.927
DR. FAUCI:<i> Although we were making</i>
<i>progress</i>

1:03:26.385 --> 1:03:30.598
in coming to some rapprochement,
as it were,

1:03:30.932 --> 1:03:36.270
they still thought that something
wasn't happening quickly enough.

1:03:38.481 --> 1:03:42.777
PETER: <i>He did not want to do anything</i>
<i>that was considered rocking the boat</i>

1:03:42.902 --> 1:03:46.072
about scientific norms
and the scientific establishment.

1:03:47.240 --> 1:03:50.868
DR. FAUCI: <i>If you don't forge ahead,</i>
<i>you get accused of being too slow.</i>

1:03:51.536 --> 1:03:54.539
<i>I'm just gonna have to do what's right</i>
<i>and do my job</i>

1:03:54.622 --> 1:03:57.291
and know that this is the right thing
for biomedical science,

1:03:57.458 --> 1:03:59.502
the right thing
for the health of this country.

1:04:00.920 --> 1:04:04.882
DR. FAUCI:<i> How you design a clinical trial</i>
<i>and how you evaluate those results,</i>

1:04:05.007 --> 1:04:10.304
the time it takes to go from the beginning
up to the time it actually gets approved

1:04:11.138 --> 1:04:15.351
were what you would refer to
as sacrosanct processes.

1:04:16.394 --> 1:04:19.397
<i>Rigidity was perfection.</i>

1:04:21.190 --> 1:04:25.278
The reasons I can't get any of these drugs
is because the leadership in this country

1:04:25.361 --> 1:04:28.114
has failed to come up
with a plan of action.

1:04:28.948 --> 1:04:30.032
PETER:<i> Bottom line.</i>

1:04:30.408 --> 1:04:34.203
The government's AIDS research effort,
which he is supposedly in charge of...

1:04:35.204 --> 1:04:36.330
isn't producing.

1:04:36.831 --> 1:04:40.835
ACT UP REP 1: The Federal Government's
AIDS research program is flawed.

1:04:41.502 --> 1:04:44.297
So, we're going to have
a small but tasteful little gathering

1:04:44.422 --> 1:04:47.466
at the National Institutes of Health
on May 21st.

1:04:47.592 --> 1:04:50.052
-(AUDIENCE APPLAUD)
-ACT UP REP 2: Storm the NIH.

1:04:50.428 --> 1:04:53.264
PETER: <i>I called Tony and I said,</i>
<i>"We're coming."</i>

1:04:55.766 --> 1:04:56.809
And it was game on.

1:04:57.768 --> 1:05:01.272
-(FAST MUSIC PLAYING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1:05:01.480 --> 1:05:03.900
Every 12 minutes someone dies.

1:05:05.276 --> 1:05:07.153
SUSAN KIDD:
<i>A group calling itself ACT UP</i>

1:05:07.236 --> 1:05:08.863
<i>wants changes in AIDS research.</i>

1:05:08.946 --> 1:05:12.617
Asking for wider and faster testing
of AIDS fighting drugs.

1:05:12.700 --> 1:05:16.829
Here's your money, NIH!
Here's your money, NIH!

1:05:17.204 --> 1:05:19.999
SUSAN SPENCER: <i>Mounted police</i>
<i>and others wearing rubber gloves</i>

1:05:20.082 --> 1:05:22.126
<i>confronted about 1,000 AIDS activists.</i>

1:05:22.293 --> 1:05:27.131
(INDISTINCT CHATTER CONTINUES)

1:05:28.090 --> 1:05:29.800
MALE PROTESTOR: <i>They won't test</i>
<i>any of these drugs</i>

1:05:29.884 --> 1:05:33.971
<i>that will keep people alive.</i>
<i>No Peptide T, no Compound Q.</i>

1:05:34.180 --> 1:05:36.265
Anthony Fauci, I piss on you.

1:05:36.432 --> 1:05:39.602
The NIH is lying!
Women with AIDS are dying!

1:05:41.187 --> 1:05:45.524
Their decisions for our women,
children, people of color is always no.

1:05:45.691 --> 1:05:48.653
Dr. Anthony Fauci
and a lot of other hotshot scientists

1:05:48.861 --> 1:05:51.113
are having conferences
deciding research priorities.

1:05:52.657 --> 1:05:54.700
We think we should be deciding
the research priorities.

1:05:54.825 --> 1:05:56.285
These are the people who know
what's going on

1:05:56.369 --> 1:05:58.079
because they're dealing with it every day.

1:06:00.706 --> 1:06:04.377
DR. FAUCI: <i>I started to put myself</i>
<i>into their shoes</i>

1:06:04.585 --> 1:06:07.421
<i>and finally I realized</i>
<i>what they really wanted</i>

1:06:07.546 --> 1:06:09.423
<i>is to be part of the process.</i>

1:06:10.132 --> 1:06:13.094
I have a disease.
I'm gonna be dead in X number of months.

1:06:13.177 --> 1:06:16.013
You've just given me a plan
that something is gonna happen

1:06:16.138 --> 1:06:17.181
in three years.

1:06:17.306 --> 1:06:19.266
Thank you very much,
but I'm gonna be dead.

1:06:19.558 --> 1:06:21.394
So we need to do a little bit more
about that.

1:06:21.477 --> 1:06:24.397
<i>Typical day at the NIH</i>
<i>watching people die!</i>

1:06:25.022 --> 1:06:27.024
DR. FAUCI:<i> And I started to feel,</i>

1:06:27.233 --> 1:06:29.527
<i>and my staff thought</i>
<i>I was completely nuts...</i>

1:06:30.361 --> 1:06:33.072
almost an affinity... to them.

1:06:37.118 --> 1:06:41.163
I pulled a banner out of my backpack
and I'm starting to tape it up

1:06:41.414 --> 1:06:45.292
<i>and then all of a sudden,</i>
<i>all these cops are lifting each other up.</i>

1:06:45.918 --> 1:06:48.170
They're angry that they've been fooled.

1:06:52.383 --> 1:06:56.595
<i>And they lower me down into the arms</i>
<i>of all the other cops.</i>

1:06:58.681 --> 1:07:01.726
<i>And the commander says,</i>
<i>"Take him through the building."</i>

1:07:03.936 --> 1:07:08.524
Halfway down the hall
I see a very familiar sight.

1:07:09.316 --> 1:07:13.946
A short man in a white coat. (LAUGHS)

1:07:16.699 --> 1:07:21.203
And, uh, he goes... "Peter?"

1:07:21.287 --> 1:07:25.207
And Peter looks me in the eye,
he says, "Tony, I did it. I got arrested.

1:07:25.291 --> 1:07:26.792
"I told you I'd get arrested."

1:07:27.001 --> 1:07:31.005
And the cop looks at me and says,
"What the shit is going on here?

1:07:31.255 --> 1:07:33.674
"Who is this guy? He's your friend?"

1:07:33.883 --> 1:07:36.802
(CHUCKLES) Because he knows
this is the Director of the Building

1:07:37.011 --> 1:07:40.389
and, like, "Who the hell is this guy
I'm arresting?"

1:07:40.598 --> 1:07:43.851
We completely befuddled the police.

1:07:46.187 --> 1:07:49.899
DAVID: <i>Tony understood that</i>
<i>what we were doing was political theater</i>

1:07:50.024 --> 1:07:51.817
<i>to move an issue along.</i>

1:07:53.319 --> 1:07:55.321
<i>He never stopped being open.</i>

1:07:55.780 --> 1:07:59.408
He never said, "The way you treated me
at that demonstration,

1:07:59.533 --> 1:08:01.285
"I'm never gonna talk
to you people again."

1:08:01.660 --> 1:08:04.955
Instead, it was exactly the opposite.
It's "We need to talk more."

1:08:08.626 --> 1:08:14.173
DR. FAUCI:<i> There was a lot of push back</i>
<i>on the part of some of my own staff,</i>

1:08:14.548 --> 1:08:18.677
that I was compromising
the scientific process.

1:08:19.053 --> 1:08:23.557
You can't have activists involved
in our meetings

1:08:23.641 --> 1:08:26.602
where we discuss the design
of a clinical trial.

1:08:29.605 --> 1:08:32.650
PETER:<i> By that summer,</i>
<i>with the International AIDS Conference</i>

1:08:32.817 --> 1:08:34.860
<i>about to happen in San Francisco,</i>

1:08:35.027 --> 1:08:37.905
<i>the relationship</i>
<i>between the scientific establishment</i>

1:08:38.364 --> 1:08:41.867
and ACT UP was at a breaking point.

1:08:44.411 --> 1:08:46.789
FORREST SAWYER: <i>About 100 protesters</i>
<i>have already been arrested</i>

1:08:46.914 --> 1:08:50.209
at the International AIDS Conference
that began today in San Francisco.

1:08:50.793 --> 1:08:53.045
MALE VOICE 17: <i>Researchers feel</i>
<i>that they're undervalued.</i>

1:08:53.295 --> 1:08:55.464
<i>If they feel that they're gonna be</i>
<i>demonstrated against,</i>

1:08:55.589 --> 1:08:57.842
they'll just get out
and do their work in cancer

1:08:58.050 --> 1:09:00.386
and Alzheimer's disease and heart,
what have you.

1:09:00.469 --> 1:09:02.763
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1:09:02.847 --> 1:09:06.767
You can beat them down
by this constant harassment.

1:09:07.852 --> 1:09:12.481
PETER:<i> Larry Kramer called for riots.</i>
<i>It was getting out of hand.</i>

1:09:13.065 --> 1:09:16.610
And then the organizers of the conference
tried to placate ACT UP.

1:09:17.403 --> 1:09:20.823
<i>They said "If you want to speak,</i>
<i>it's yours."</i>

1:09:21.282 --> 1:09:22.741
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1:09:22.867 --> 1:09:27.413
PETER: Exactly 30 days ago,
all of us here in the front

1:09:28.164 --> 1:09:31.250
stood up for what we believed in
and vocalized our commitment

1:09:31.542 --> 1:09:34.628
on the beautiful grounds
of the National Institutes of Health.

1:09:36.463 --> 1:09:39.091
When we make mistakes, what's the fallout?

1:09:39.925 --> 1:09:43.220
Some people become offended
and begin to hate ACT UP.

1:09:44.555 --> 1:09:48.350
Whereas, when government
or scientific community makes a mistake,

1:09:48.684 --> 1:09:50.853
thousands of people can die.

1:09:53.105 --> 1:09:58.152
It became patently clear to me
that they were making absolute sense.

1:09:58.235 --> 1:10:00.571
It gives me great pleasure
to welcome Dr. Fauci.

1:10:00.654 --> 1:10:01.822
It's an honor to have him here.

1:10:01.947 --> 1:10:05.951
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD)

1:10:09.371 --> 1:10:13.042
AIDS in the 1990s has revolutionized
the relationship

1:10:13.125 --> 1:10:14.752
between the public and scientists.

1:10:15.586 --> 1:10:18.964
The politically charged nature
of the epidemic has put researchers

1:10:19.048 --> 1:10:21.592
under an extraordinary degree
of public scrutiny.

1:10:22.676 --> 1:10:26.555
They are confronted with the accusation
by some that they are not doing enough

1:10:26.639 --> 1:10:28.224
and that they are moving too slowly.

1:10:28.349 --> 1:10:32.353
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD, CHEER)

1:10:32.478 --> 1:10:33.562
I'm not finished.

1:10:36.774 --> 1:10:40.486
The scientific process is often seen
as overly restrictive

1:10:40.569 --> 1:10:42.279
and even an impediment to solution.

1:10:43.197 --> 1:10:48.369
<i>The most vocal, provocative</i>
<i>and articulate groups among these</i>

1:10:48.494 --> 1:10:49.995
<i>are the AIDS Activists.</i>

1:10:50.371 --> 1:10:54.583
Some of them are better informed
than many scientists can possibly imagine.

1:10:59.004 --> 1:11:01.924
Yet they are sometimes incorrect.

1:11:02.049 --> 1:11:03.133
(CHUCKLES)

1:11:05.261 --> 1:11:06.845
Believe it or not. (LAUGHS)

1:11:06.929 --> 1:11:08.222
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

1:11:08.305 --> 1:11:10.849
However, in the interactions

1:11:10.933 --> 1:11:13.352
between physicians, scientists
and activists,

1:11:13.560 --> 1:11:16.188
mistakes have been made by both sides.

1:11:17.064 --> 1:11:22.236
Activists are mistaken when they assume
that scientists do not care about them.

1:11:23.279 --> 1:11:25.948
This is devastating
to a physician scientist

1:11:26.073 --> 1:11:28.325
who has devoted years to AIDS research,

1:11:28.492 --> 1:11:30.494
<i>particularly when they themselves</i>

1:11:30.619 --> 1:11:33.497
<i>see so many of their own patients</i>
<i>suffering and dying.</i>

1:11:34.581 --> 1:11:38.085
<i>On the other hand,</i>
<i>scientists cannot dismiss activists</i>

1:11:38.335 --> 1:11:42.214
<i>merely on the basis of the fact</i>
<i>that they are not trained scientists.</i>

1:11:43.007 --> 1:11:46.510
Activists bring a very special insight
into the disease

1:11:46.719 --> 1:11:49.013
that they can actually be helpful

1:11:49.263 --> 1:11:52.683
in the way that we design
our scientific approaches.

1:11:53.892 --> 1:11:58.605
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD)

1:12:00.274 --> 1:12:03.986
We must join together,
for together we a formidable force

1:12:04.194 --> 1:12:05.487
with a common goal.

1:12:05.779 --> 1:12:09.533
We must never lose sight of the fact
that the people whom we serve

1:12:09.616 --> 1:12:12.786
are the HIV infected people
throughout the world. Thank you.

1:12:19.001 --> 1:12:25.341
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD, CHEER)

1:12:29.053 --> 1:12:32.056
DR. FAUCI:<i> During that speech,</i>
<i>I'm saying something</i>

1:12:32.139 --> 1:12:34.683
and you have the activists clap.

1:12:35.184 --> 1:12:38.270
Then I say something
and the scientists clap.

1:12:38.771 --> 1:12:44.943
The beauty of it is that...
at the end of it, everybody was clapping.

1:12:48.614 --> 1:12:51.075
ROBERT VAZQUEZ-PACHECO: <i>The AIDS activists</i>
<i>went from being the adversaries</i>

1:12:51.533 --> 1:12:53.410
to actually the people
who were sitting down

1:12:53.494 --> 1:12:55.662
at the table with us discussing
what is happening.

1:12:56.914 --> 1:13:01.835
And that is a huge shift.
That changed everything.

1:13:02.378 --> 1:13:06.423
We were able to redesign
clinical trials for HIV.

1:13:07.591 --> 1:13:11.095
<i>Black people, Brown people,</i>
<i>pregnant women,</i>

1:13:11.220 --> 1:13:13.472
<i>young people were included.</i>

1:13:13.931 --> 1:13:17.601
I'm putting myself at your disposal now.
If I don't have an answer for it...

1:13:17.684 --> 1:13:19.937
ED BRADLEY:<i> And your thinking,</i>
<i>has it changed your approach</i>

1:13:20.062 --> 1:13:21.688
<i>to research on life threatening disease?</i>

1:13:21.772 --> 1:13:24.650
Rather than a real abrupt change,
I think it's an evolution.

1:13:25.818 --> 1:13:31.115
You try harder to put yourself
into the position of a patient.

1:13:33.075 --> 1:13:35.911
DAVID: <i>This whole notion of understanding</i>
<i>that we have a value</i>

1:13:36.537 --> 1:13:37.830
in those discussions

1:13:38.080 --> 1:13:41.834
changed the shape of clinical research
and drug development.

1:13:42.251 --> 1:13:44.420
And it went well beyond AIDS.

1:13:44.628 --> 1:13:46.839
-What do we want?
-A cure!

1:13:47.005 --> 1:13:49.049
-When do we want it?
-Now!

1:13:51.009 --> 1:13:53.887
DAVID:<i> Now it happens in cancer</i>
<i>and it happens in Alzheimer's</i>

1:13:54.012 --> 1:13:56.557
<i>and it happens</i>
<i>in all these different disease areas.</i>

1:13:58.851 --> 1:14:00.394
<i>Science has realized</i>

1:14:00.519 --> 1:14:02.980
you need to include these voices
in the process

1:14:03.063 --> 1:14:05.065
because it makes for better science.

1:14:06.483 --> 1:14:09.611
<i>And Tony is the one who opened that door.</i>

1:14:10.487 --> 1:14:13.991
We're the ones who knocked on that door
and pushed that door

1:14:14.199 --> 1:14:15.534
and barged our way in.

1:14:15.742 --> 1:14:18.120
But Tony understood the value of it
early on.

1:14:18.203 --> 1:14:21.457
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDS, CHEERS)

1:14:22.291 --> 1:14:26.253
DR. FAUCI: <i>The difference now</i>
<i>is that divisiveness</i>

1:14:26.670 --> 1:14:30.007
<i>is dominating COVID-19.</i>

1:14:32.301 --> 1:14:35.304
I don't see them ever clapping together.

1:14:36.054 --> 1:14:37.598
I think we're gonna get through it.

1:14:39.433 --> 1:14:45.772
But we're gonna get through it
in spite of this divisiveness

1:14:45.939 --> 1:14:47.983
and this politicization.

1:14:48.817 --> 1:14:51.987
We're not gonna get through it
because of it.

1:15:02.706 --> 1:15:05.292
(PHONE RINGING)

1:15:08.003 --> 1:15:10.714
-DR. FAUCI: <i>Peter!</i>
-PETER:<i> Hey. How are you?</i>

1:15:11.673 --> 1:15:13.008
DR. FAUCI:<i> Oh, I'm all right.</i>

1:15:13.550 --> 1:15:18.055
These fucking dark web people

1:15:18.138 --> 1:15:19.890
-are really, really getting bad.
-PETER:<i> All right.</i>

1:15:19.973 --> 1:15:22.601
They're really, really harassing Chris.

1:15:22.893 --> 1:15:27.606
One of them called up...
with violent threats,

1:15:27.940 --> 1:15:30.192
like eight times today
on her cell phone

1:15:30.317 --> 1:15:32.569
until she figured I've got to just change
my cell phone.

1:15:33.320 --> 1:15:37.908
You know, they're harassing
my daughters constantly,

1:15:37.991 --> 1:15:40.077
which it really bothers me
more than anything else.

1:15:40.619 --> 1:15:43.247
PETER: <i>Remind her that almost all of them</i>
<i>are cowards.</i>

1:15:43.455 --> 1:15:44.665
-Yeah.
-PETER: <i>All just...</i>

1:15:44.957 --> 1:15:47.125
Well, that's
what my Secret Service detail says.

1:15:47.209 --> 1:15:48.293
-They say... I mean...
-PETER: <i>Yeah.</i>

1:15:48.377 --> 1:15:50.212
Because they have a lot of experience
with this.

1:15:50.587 --> 1:15:52.923
And, you know, they don't want
to make light of it,

1:15:53.048 --> 1:15:56.301
but they say that most of them
are just a bunch of fricking cowards.

1:15:57.219 --> 1:16:00.055
PETER:<i> They want to scare you all.</i>

1:16:00.138 --> 1:16:02.349
-Right.
-PETER: <i>They want you to back down.</i>

1:16:02.474 --> 1:16:03.600
Right.

1:16:04.226 --> 1:16:07.479
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

1:16:07.646 --> 1:16:12.067
When COVID hit, at first, it was like,
oh, my God,

1:16:12.234 --> 1:16:15.153
give Tony space while he does his thing.

1:16:15.487 --> 1:16:17.197
Uh, don't overwhelm him.

1:16:17.906 --> 1:16:19.783
Let's try to figure out
what's going wrong.

1:16:20.659 --> 1:16:26.164
<i>And then when he became this target,</i>

1:16:26.456 --> 1:16:28.250
I just kept checking in.

1:16:31.503 --> 1:16:33.088
(ENGINE STARTING)

1:16:33.380 --> 1:16:37.342
JENNY:<i> For me and my sisters</i>
<i>this was really, really new territory.</i>

1:16:38.260 --> 1:16:42.264
<i>We heard about what he went through</i>
<i>in the HIV AIDS pandemic.</i>

1:16:43.765 --> 1:16:46.560
<i>Like seeing signs, you know,</i>
<i>"Fauci is a murderer."</i>

1:16:47.853 --> 1:16:50.606
And I remember asking him, like,
"Is this what it was like?

1:16:50.731 --> 1:16:54.234
"Was I just not old enough to understand,
but this is actually what it was like?"

1:16:54.735 --> 1:16:57.195
And, you know,
his response is something like,

1:16:57.654 --> 1:17:00.991
"You can't even compare the two.
This is so beyond the beyond."

1:17:04.244 --> 1:17:06.371
DR. FAUCI:<i> The whole atmosphere...</i>

1:17:07.039 --> 1:17:11.251
<i>strains your concept of what normality is.</i>

1:17:14.713 --> 1:17:16.923
<i>You know, and just when you think</i>
<i>everything is okay,</i>

1:17:17.007 --> 1:17:19.217
<i>I was sitting at my desk</i>
<i>and I opened up a letter</i>

1:17:19.384 --> 1:17:21.178
and a puff of powder came up.

1:17:22.179 --> 1:17:26.183
It was on my shirt, my tie, my pants,
my hands and my chin.

1:17:26.767 --> 1:17:28.393
The first thing I thought of was,

1:17:28.518 --> 1:17:30.979
"Holy shit,
why did I open up this letter?"

1:17:32.814 --> 1:17:36.652
<i>And then the options started</i>
<i>to crystallize in my mind.</i>

1:17:37.694 --> 1:17:40.572
One, it's a hoax.

1:17:41.114 --> 1:17:45.702
Two, it's anthrax
and I'm gonna get sick,

1:17:45.786 --> 1:17:47.996
but I'm gonna take Cipro
and I'm gonna be okay.

1:17:48.538 --> 1:17:52.501
Or three, it's Ricin
and I'm freakin' dead.

1:17:58.090 --> 1:18:00.884
<i>Fortunately, it turned out to be a hoax.</i>

1:18:02.219 --> 1:18:05.013
JENNY: <i>My sisters and I</i>
<i>were really worried.</i>

1:18:06.348 --> 1:18:08.642
And that was...

1:18:09.685 --> 1:18:12.979
It continues to be really disturbing,
really unsettling.

1:18:17.526 --> 1:18:20.070
I don't understand the hate
that people have.

1:18:20.570 --> 1:18:23.657
And the hate that leads them
to do something

1:18:23.824 --> 1:18:25.784
that could hurt somebody
or kill somebody.

1:18:26.076 --> 1:18:31.957
I mean, it sort of... reduces my trust
in humanity

1:18:32.708 --> 1:18:35.711
in a way that is probably impossible
to measure.

1:18:35.794 --> 1:18:37.462
But certainly, I felt it.

1:18:49.683 --> 1:18:50.934
(GRUNTS)

1:19:08.910 --> 1:19:13.457
I never, for a moment,
thought that I should resign.

1:19:14.708 --> 1:19:17.127
<i>I just never thought about it.</i>

1:19:21.131 --> 1:19:22.591
<i>I just said to myself...</i>

1:19:23.550 --> 1:19:26.303
<i>focus on what you're trying to do.</i>

1:19:29.181 --> 1:19:34.186
<i>Is what you're trying to do more important</i>
<i>than all of this other peripheral crap?</i>

1:19:36.271 --> 1:19:40.358
<i>If it is, just focus like a laser</i>
<i>and go for it.</i>

1:19:42.944 --> 1:19:43.987
<i>Okay.</i>

1:19:44.571 --> 1:19:47.073
I just realized that I haven't had
a good night's sleep

1:19:47.199 --> 1:19:48.533
in a very, very long time.

1:19:48.825 --> 1:19:52.871
I'm waiting until the first person
enters into the phase three trial...

1:19:52.996 --> 1:19:54.164
(MAN LAUGHING)

1:19:54.247 --> 1:19:56.541
...and then,
I'll have a good night's sleep, so.

1:19:57.125 --> 1:19:58.835
FEMALE VOICE: <i>That will be Moderna,</i>
<i>mRNA.</i>

1:19:59.002 --> 1:20:01.671
No, no. I know that,
but I'm holding my breath

1:20:02.297 --> 1:20:03.507
until that happens.

1:20:04.549 --> 1:20:06.468
It must be something psychological.

1:20:06.760 --> 1:20:10.096
I keep waking up at 2:30
'til quarter to three in the morning.

1:20:12.057 --> 1:20:16.061
DR. FAUCI:
<i>Despite this extraordinary divisiveness...</i>

1:20:16.853 --> 1:20:20.232
it was very clear we were dealing
with a common enemy

1:20:20.774 --> 1:20:23.401
and the common enemy was the virus.

1:20:25.445 --> 1:20:29.950
I really do hope that somehow or other
there is a realization

1:20:30.325 --> 1:20:33.036
that we can't go on this way,

1:20:33.370 --> 1:20:37.374
because it's a lesson that will be,
I think, important for us

1:20:37.582 --> 1:20:39.793
to adequately respond
to the next outbreak,

1:20:39.918 --> 1:20:42.087
which inevitably will occur.

1:20:42.212 --> 1:20:46.466
Maybe not in my lifetime, maybe it will,
but it will occur.

1:20:50.262 --> 1:20:54.140
My dad said on TV, on the radio,
to me, to my mom,

1:20:54.266 --> 1:20:57.727
to my sisters, like,
"We're gonna get through it."

1:20:58.270 --> 1:21:01.523
And he's held that with him
through this whole thing,

1:21:01.940 --> 1:21:04.568
when so many people, the whole country,

1:21:04.651 --> 1:21:07.070
so many of us have struggled to think,
are we ever gonna get through this thing?

1:21:07.696 --> 1:21:10.156
-Are you all set?
-MALE VOICE: I know.

1:21:10.282 --> 1:21:12.409
JENNY:<i> Somehow he's been able</i>
<i>to hold onto that</i>

1:21:12.492 --> 1:21:17.247
<i>because he's lived in times</i>
<i>where it felt like a thing couldn't end.</i>

1:21:18.915 --> 1:21:20.584
(KEYBOARD KEYS CLATTERING)

1:21:24.254 --> 1:21:26.631
(MUSIC PLAYING)

1:21:27.132 --> 1:21:29.384
BROKAW: <i>The search</i>
<i>for an AIDS vaccine...</i>

1:21:29.885 --> 1:21:31.636
<i>that hope now has dimmed.</i>

1:21:32.095 --> 1:21:35.974
More than a decade into the AIDS epidemic,
we're still nowhere close to a cure.

1:21:36.725 --> 1:21:38.768
KEN ARMINGTON:
<i>Since the late '80s, we've seen</i>

1:21:38.852 --> 1:21:40.145
<i>pretty splashy reports in the media</i>

1:21:40.270 --> 1:21:42.272
<i>about drugs that worked well</i>
<i>in the test tube</i>

1:21:42.522 --> 1:21:45.650
and then find out in a few months
that they did not work in people.

1:21:46.943 --> 1:21:49.446
FEMALE REPORTER:
<i>This is the bitter new reality of AIDS.</i>

1:21:49.821 --> 1:21:53.074
<i>There are more drugs around</i>
<i>to prolong patients' lives,</i>

1:21:53.491 --> 1:21:56.286
<i>but their deaths</i>
<i>are more excruciating than ever.</i>

1:21:56.912 --> 1:21:59.748
The biomedical research community
is suffering,

1:21:59.956 --> 1:22:01.583
for not having solved the problem.

1:22:02.083 --> 1:22:04.753
<i>Our country says,</i>
<i>"Why can't you guys do this?"</i>

1:22:05.712 --> 1:22:07.756
DR. FAUCI:<i> It is conceivable</i>
<i>that we will never get a vaccine.</i>

1:22:07.839 --> 1:22:09.549
<i>I think we have to face that reality.</i>

1:22:09.633 --> 1:22:11.468
People sometimes hesitate
to talk about that

1:22:11.551 --> 1:22:14.346
because it gets taken out of context
and people say well, they're giving up.

1:22:14.429 --> 1:22:15.639
No-one is giving up.

1:22:19.434 --> 1:22:21.269
DR. FAUCI: <i>There were a number of studies</i>
<i>that were going on</i>

1:22:21.353 --> 1:22:23.521
<i>that were funded by my institute.</i>

1:22:24.564 --> 1:22:27.359
<i>We had gradual progress...</i>

1:22:28.193 --> 1:22:30.070
but never the home run.

1:22:31.488 --> 1:22:35.659
<i>And then, in 1996,</i>
<i>there are a couple of studies</i>

1:22:36.034 --> 1:22:42.207
that incorporated protease inhibitors
as one of three drugs

1:22:42.624 --> 1:22:44.167
that were given in combination.

1:22:44.501 --> 1:22:45.794
On <i>Close Up</i> this morning,

1:22:45.877 --> 1:22:48.088
reports of possible new treatments
for AIDS.

1:22:48.213 --> 1:22:50.799
ELIZABETH KALEDIN: <i>AIDS drugs known</i>
<i>as protease inhibitors</i>

1:22:50.882 --> 1:22:54.511
<i>may actually eliminate the AIDS virus</i>
<i>in human tissue.</i>

1:22:56.429 --> 1:22:58.932
I'd had the pneumonias
and I was getting skinnier...

1:22:59.641 --> 1:23:01.518
and I didn't have much fight left in me.

1:23:02.227 --> 1:23:06.022
<i>And I got down here with NIH in 1995</i>

1:23:06.606 --> 1:23:08.942
<i>and I was one of the first people</i>
<i>in the country</i>

1:23:09.067 --> 1:23:10.360
<i>that was given the cocktail.</i>

1:23:11.069 --> 1:23:13.738
And seven days later,
my numbers had started to change.

1:23:14.698 --> 1:23:17.033
And my T cells started to rise and...

1:23:18.952 --> 1:23:20.954
my viral burden started to go down.

1:23:23.623 --> 1:23:25.166
I just need a second. Uh...

1:23:30.338 --> 1:23:32.590
(SIGHS) Um...

1:23:36.344 --> 1:23:38.054
That was the moment that changed my life.

1:23:41.057 --> 1:23:43.268
<i>I started getting better.</i>

1:23:46.855 --> 1:23:50.025
LAURIE:<i> Immune systems are restoring</i>
<i>back to normalcy,</i>

1:23:50.483 --> 1:23:52.152
the virus is disappearing.

1:23:52.360 --> 1:23:55.447
It's gotten to levels so low,
it can't even be found.

1:23:55.697 --> 1:23:57.741
It's called the AIDS cocktail.

1:23:57.991 --> 1:24:01.536
And the success of the cocktail
is the first real sign

1:24:01.619 --> 1:24:04.372
that the AIDS epidemic
may not be invincible.

1:24:05.582 --> 1:24:08.168
CLIFF: <i>It really was, like,</i>
<i>the most amazing thing</i>

1:24:08.668 --> 1:24:12.422
to go from a physician
to terminally ill patients

1:24:12.839 --> 1:24:15.341
to a physician who could prevent people
from dying.

1:24:16.885 --> 1:24:19.971
DR. FAUCI:<i> It's the best we've seen</i>
<i>thus far with any drugs.</i>

1:24:20.722 --> 1:24:22.015
The effects are profound.

1:24:22.098 --> 1:24:26.144
I'm certain they're going to be translated
into positive clinical benefits.

1:24:26.561 --> 1:24:29.022
DAVID SANFORD:<i> I no longer feel</i>
<i>as though I'm dying, I no longer crave it.</i>

1:24:29.105 --> 1:24:32.275
I don't have contingency plans
to end my life.

1:24:32.358 --> 1:24:36.738
I'm not in that mode at all.
I'm back among the living.

1:24:37.113 --> 1:24:39.074
I'm a grandmother,
but that's only one grandchild.

1:24:39.157 --> 1:24:41.034
I still have two other children
that don't have children.

1:24:41.367 --> 1:24:42.952
You know, I want a house full.

1:24:43.369 --> 1:24:46.164
And if I keep taking my medicine
I'm gonna be here

1:24:46.247 --> 1:24:48.166
to rock every single one of them
on my lap.

1:24:48.249 --> 1:24:52.712
It's nice to have new things
down the road to look forward to.

1:24:52.879 --> 1:24:55.131
Yeah, I feel like I'm 16 again,
it's great. (LAUGHS)

1:24:56.007 --> 1:24:58.301
Every birthday since I've been 35...

1:24:59.511 --> 1:25:01.596
there isn't one birthday, not one,

1:25:02.347 --> 1:25:06.684
that I don't thank him
for what he has done for me.

1:25:14.025 --> 1:25:19.697
My dad turned 80 this year
and it was the first birthday,

1:25:19.781 --> 1:25:23.034
Christmas Eve, Christmas
that we weren't all together.

1:25:25.578 --> 1:25:27.330
<i>Since I was a little kid,</i>

1:25:27.455 --> 1:25:29.040
I've often taken the role of...

1:25:30.917 --> 1:25:33.628
you know, telling him,
like, "You have to take a break.

1:25:33.753 --> 1:25:35.797
"You have to slow down.
You have to take care of yourself."

1:25:37.215 --> 1:25:40.260
<i>But I saw that as long</i>
<i>as the COVID pandemic</i>

1:25:40.677 --> 1:25:43.096
was happening, he was gonna be all in.

1:25:44.264 --> 1:25:48.768
<i>So, I tried to be there for him</i>
<i>in a different kind of way from afar.</i>

1:25:50.311 --> 1:25:54.232
<i>Checking in with him, calling him,</i>
<i>sending him text messages of birds,</i>

1:25:54.357 --> 1:25:57.193
sending him pictures of my dog.
Something to keep him going.

1:26:00.029 --> 1:26:02.907
DR. FAUCI: <i>Right now,</i>
<i>what I'm going through...</i>

1:26:03.950 --> 1:26:07.912
is kind of like a diabolical repeat...

1:26:08.872 --> 1:26:13.960
of what went on
back when they were children growing up.

1:26:14.961 --> 1:26:21.134
<i>But now they're adults</i>
<i>and they see what I'm going through...</i>

1:26:21.968 --> 1:26:23.428
<i>and what Chris is going through.</i>

1:26:24.387 --> 1:26:30.768
<i>And... they are just amazingly supportive</i>

1:26:31.227 --> 1:26:32.437
<i>and proud.</i>

1:26:33.438 --> 1:26:36.774
-CHRISTINE:<i> Hi, Ali.</i>
-DR. FAUCI:<i> Hey, Ali, babe. Hey, Jane.</i>

1:26:37.108 --> 1:26:38.943
-CHRISTINE:<i> Megan's there too.</i>
-DR. FAUCI: <i>Hey, Megan D.</i>

1:26:39.402 --> 1:26:42.197
Hi, sweet thing. I love you.

1:26:42.780 --> 1:26:44.073
<i>-I love you too.</i>
-DR. FAUCI: Take care.

1:26:44.866 --> 1:26:46.284
I wish you guys were here.

1:26:49.454 --> 1:26:51.164
(WATER RUNNING)

1:26:51.497 --> 1:26:54.167
JENNY:<i> As much as I've given my dad</i>
<i>a hard time my whole life,</i>

1:26:54.792 --> 1:26:59.214
I'm so grateful to see an example
of what it means

1:26:59.422 --> 1:27:03.301
to stay committed to who you are
and stay committed to what you believe in.

1:27:03.468 --> 1:27:06.638
(BELL RINGING)

1:27:10.266 --> 1:27:11.351
DR. FAUCI:<i> With HIV AIDS,</i>

1:27:11.684 --> 1:27:14.687
<i>when we finally nailed down</i>
<i>the triple combination</i>

1:27:14.771 --> 1:27:17.565
<i>that brought down the level of virus</i>
<i>to below detectable,</i>

1:27:17.941 --> 1:27:19.817
<i>it was close to euphoria.</i>

1:27:21.069 --> 1:27:22.320
<i>People were going back</i>

1:27:22.403 --> 1:27:27.367
to what turned out to be
a semi normal existence.

1:27:27.742 --> 1:27:32.747
But that then shined a bright light
on the disparity

1:27:33.206 --> 1:27:35.959
between the developed world
and the developing world.

1:27:36.167 --> 1:27:39.462
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

1:27:48.012 --> 1:27:49.514
PETER MUGYENYI:

1:28:10.660 --> 1:28:15.123
BONO: <i>Inequality raises its head</i>
<i>in many different ways in our world.</i>

1:28:15.623 --> 1:28:18.209
HIV AIDS, it was very clear...

1:28:19.043 --> 1:28:21.754
we could get those pills
for those people or not.

1:28:22.964 --> 1:28:26.301
What would that cost to give patients
the drugs that they need?

1:28:26.634 --> 1:28:28.553
Six hundred US dollars per month.

1:28:28.803 --> 1:28:30.972
And a man like this,
how much would he make a month?

1:28:31.097 --> 1:28:33.016
Maybe five, ten dollars.

1:28:33.349 --> 1:28:34.684
MUGYENYI:

1:28:48.031 --> 1:28:52.327
TOM: <i>The perspective was,</i>
<i>we'll never be able to do that in Africa,</i>

1:28:52.410 --> 1:28:54.203
for all sorts of crazy reasons.

1:28:54.829 --> 1:28:57.206
Not enough money,
people wouldn't take medications,

1:28:57.332 --> 1:28:58.374
it's impossible.

1:28:58.499 --> 1:29:01.711
These drugs have to be administered
during a certain sequence

1:29:01.878 --> 1:29:03.087
at a time during the day

1:29:03.338 --> 1:29:05.006
and when you say,
"Take it at ten o'clock."

1:29:05.131 --> 1:29:07.425
People will say,
"What do you mean by ten o'clock?"

1:29:08.217 --> 1:29:10.011
If you've traveled rural Africa,
you know this.

1:29:10.136 --> 1:29:12.263
This is not a criticism,
just a different world.

1:29:12.722 --> 1:29:14.974
People do not know
what watches and clocks are.

1:29:15.058 --> 1:29:19.479
They do not use Western means
for telling the time. They use the sun.

1:29:21.981 --> 1:29:25.276
GEORGE BUSH: <i>Early in my Administration,</i>
<i>Condi Rice said "Mr. President,</i>

1:29:25.401 --> 1:29:29.322
<i>"are you aware there's a pandemic</i>
<i>destroying an entire generation of people</i>

1:29:29.405 --> 1:29:30.698
<i>in the continent of Africa?"</i>

1:29:31.449 --> 1:29:33.242
<i>I said,</i>
<i>"We need to do something about it."</i>

1:29:33.951 --> 1:29:37.580
People in my Administration
whose judgment I trust said, you know,

1:29:37.705 --> 1:29:38.706
"Unleash Fauci."

1:29:41.334 --> 1:29:43.753
<i>Tony Fauci doesn't come</i>
<i>in the Oval Office and say,</i>

1:29:43.836 --> 1:29:46.047
"I'm gonna make you look good
politically."

1:29:47.423 --> 1:29:48.800
He's not a politician.

1:29:50.802 --> 1:29:54.347
<i>Tony Fauci says,</i>
<i>"I think we can solve this problem.</i>

1:29:54.722 --> 1:29:55.848
<i>"Here are the facts,</i>

1:29:56.015 --> 1:29:58.684
and here's my recommendation
for a way forward."

1:30:00.645 --> 1:30:04.107
DR. FAUCI:<i> So, President Bush told me,</i>
<i>"Go to Africa</i>

1:30:04.190 --> 1:30:07.902
and scout it out.
See if there's something that we can do."

1:30:11.447 --> 1:30:15.326
DR. FAUCI:<i> In Uganda, what we saw was,</i>
<i>I believe,</i>

1:30:15.410 --> 1:30:18.204
<i>what many people think</i>
<i>would not be able to be effected...</i>

1:30:18.329 --> 1:30:22.625
<i>...and that is groups of volunteers</i>
<i>on motorcycles and jeeps</i>

1:30:22.834 --> 1:30:28.047
<i>going into the very, very rural areas,</i>
<i>into the homes of people</i>

1:30:28.214 --> 1:30:30.299
<i>and delivering drugs.</i>

1:30:30.716 --> 1:30:32.176
MUGYENYI:

1:30:39.392 --> 1:30:42.353
DR. FAUCI: <i>I remember going</i>
<i>into a thatched hut.</i>

1:30:42.854 --> 1:30:44.147
<i>"How are you doing?" "Fine."</i>

1:30:44.397 --> 1:30:47.567
<i>"You're taking your medicines?"</i>
<i>"Yes, I'm taking them very regularly."</i>

1:30:47.900 --> 1:30:49.902
"You understand
what the medicine is doing?"

1:30:50.611 --> 1:30:53.948
"Yes, it's blocking the virus
that's killing my CD4 cells."

1:30:54.282 --> 1:30:56.033
Like, what? (LAUGHS)

1:30:57.493 --> 1:31:00.121
<i>All of this stuff that people were saying,</i>

1:31:00.204 --> 1:31:03.332
that Africans don't have
whatever it is it takes

1:31:03.916 --> 1:31:07.253
to understand the importance
of taking their drug regularly

1:31:07.628 --> 1:31:11.048
was clearly, you know,
unmitigated bullshit.

1:31:12.717 --> 1:31:18.890
We put together a model
that was a phenomenally expanded version

1:31:19.307 --> 1:31:21.184
of what Peter Mugyenyi was already doing.

1:31:21.976 --> 1:31:25.897
<i>He had people delivering drugs</i>
<i>that weren't even nurses</i>

1:31:26.022 --> 1:31:30.610
<i>on motorcycles into the bush.</i>
<i>You know, hundreds of miles away.</i>

1:31:31.068 --> 1:31:32.778
And people would take the drug.

1:31:32.862 --> 1:31:35.406
They knew what they were doing.
You could get their viral load down.

1:31:35.698 --> 1:31:37.575
All you needed to do
was to give them the drugs.

1:31:38.910 --> 1:31:44.624
<i>So, I put forth to the president</i>
<i>a 15 billion dollar program called PEPFAR.</i>

1:31:45.458 --> 1:31:48.794
The President's Emergency Plan
For AIDS Relief.

1:31:50.087 --> 1:31:52.673
I ask the Congress to commit
15 billion dollars

1:31:52.757 --> 1:31:54.091
over the next five years,

1:31:54.425 --> 1:31:56.969
including nearly ten billion dollars
in new money

1:31:57.512 --> 1:32:01.390
to turn the tide against AIDS
in the most afflicted nations of Africa

1:32:01.557 --> 1:32:02.642
and the Caribbean.

1:32:03.434 --> 1:32:06.854
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD)

1:32:07.230 --> 1:32:13.694
Fifteen billion dollars. Boom!
It was just the most magnificent moment,

1:32:14.320 --> 1:32:17.198
uh, because I knew what that really meant.

1:32:18.866 --> 1:32:20.910
MUGYENYI:

1:32:34.924 --> 1:32:38.302
DR. FAUCI: <i>We're talking</i>
<i>about preventing seven million infections.</i>

1:32:38.386 --> 1:32:42.640
In other words, seven million people
who otherwise would have gotten infected

1:32:42.723 --> 1:32:44.934
and with no therapy would have died.

1:32:45.560 --> 1:32:48.437
MUGYENYI:

1:32:57.029 --> 1:32:59.073
FEMALE VOICE:

1:33:04.495 --> 1:33:07.373
BILL GATES:<i> PEPFAR was a huge milestone,</i>

1:33:07.498 --> 1:33:10.668
this, you know,
miraculous AIDS intervention

1:33:10.793 --> 1:33:15.131
that... continues to save
tens of millions of lives.

1:33:15.798 --> 1:33:18.801
TOM: <i>It's the largest</i>
<i>bilateral program in health</i>

1:33:18.968 --> 1:33:20.511
<i>ever created anywhere</i>

1:33:20.595 --> 1:33:24.432
and Tony was an early architect of it
and it changed the world.

1:33:25.433 --> 1:33:31.147
BONO:<i> Tony's been made the size</i>
<i>of the tasks he takes on.</i>

1:33:31.439 --> 1:33:36.527
He becomes the size of the challenge
he faces each time.

1:33:38.404 --> 1:33:42.033
AIDS is one of the most
devastating scourges in human history.

1:33:42.575 --> 1:33:46.412
The US President's Emergency Plan
For AIDS Relief has done heroic work

1:33:46.495 --> 1:33:49.248
in making AIDS drugs available
to those who need them.

1:33:49.832 --> 1:33:53.294
Striving for universal access
to AIDS therapies

1:33:53.377 --> 1:33:58.841
is a public health and moral imperative
that should be embraced by all.

1:33:58.966 --> 1:34:03.054
(AUDIENCE APPLAUD)

1:34:03.638 --> 1:34:09.018
I mean that, to me, is, you know,
one of the great success stories

1:34:09.101 --> 1:34:10.436
in all of medicine.

1:34:12.313 --> 1:34:14.565
<i>When you have a global pandemic,</i>

1:34:14.982 --> 1:34:19.028
you absolutely need a global solution.

1:34:21.697 --> 1:34:24.533
<i>To think that you can take care</i>
<i>of yourself</i>

1:34:24.784 --> 1:34:28.871
without taking care
of the rest of the world is just folly.

1:34:37.046 --> 1:34:40.925
(SOFT MUSIC PLAYING)

1:34:42.843 --> 1:34:47.723
